>recoil offset by proper design
It certainly can be ... TO AN EXTENT ... depending on cartridge and gun. This means that .45 ACP can only be 'softened' so much, and part of the design to accomplish that is to increase the weight of the weapon. A 1911a is gonna kick like a mule almost no matter what, even though it's pretty heavy relative to 'typical' guns. There has been some improvement in the last two decades, but it's still a beast to shoot and of course doesn't affect post-WWII era experiences & decisions. Has double-stacked magazine now, so you get 10+1 or 12+1 in most, which increases weight, until you fire the first 6 rounds or so. That's balanced by modern .45 ACP rounds now using modern powder & heavier bullets, so .45 ACP+ rounds bring the kick back up despite compensation in the design.

There is a modern revolver design, BTW, that does a great job of reducing kick. The barrel fires off the bottom of the cylinder, which drops the center of gravity significantly. You can get a high powered .357 mag. cartridge tamed down in the range of an old .38 Special with a Chiappa. Or use .38 Special in it for a much tamer & easy to handle experience for some real precision shooting.

Barrel length is a consideration. If you want a lighter gun, a 4 inch (or shorter) barrel is one way to help. But, using heavier cartridges becomes pointless because you start burning more powder outside the barrel rather than getting useful energy out of the bullet, but still have to eat (most of) the kick. Meaning, a .357 out of a 2" barrel is largely a waste, you might as well use a .38 Special if you're goal is reducing kick & weight.

As far as Japanese police go, I don't know all their reasons, but I do know one is hard core training to NEVER need a gun except extreme circumstances. So it's considered useless weight for a skilled officer, and an absolute last resort ALWAYS. They're pretty upset if an officer uses 2 shots when he "should" have used one. It's a big deal.

Pay attention to the weight of the bullet you're shooting vs. velocity. This impacts the recoil, but also the effectiveness.

Usually you want a high velocity round, something that reaches your target at up to & around 2000 feet per second. But, if you're using a solid bullet vs. a hollow point makes big difference, since a solid round at those velocities almost always over-penetrates. Almost all handgun encounters are at between 5 meters and 15 meters, with 25+ meters getting very rare. If you're using a monster cartridge at P+ or +P+ pressures, especially with a lighter solid bullet, you can easily kill people behind the person you intend to shoot. This is an extreme situation where you'd want that kind of power if you expect to be shooting at an armored enemy.

Turns out, for typical civilian-tier self defense, you're vastly better off with a lower velocity round about 950 fps up to ~1200 fps, and a heavier hollow point bullet. If the guy you're shooting happens to be wearing protective armor, you can be screwed (shot placement shot placement shot placement). But that's almost unheard of in typical situations. So, a 190 to 220 grain hollow point from a .41 mag with a powder charge/barrel length that produces 1150-ish fps would usually be a near-optimum choice to get someone's attention.

That's why .45 ACP. They spit out 220 to 260 grain solid bullets at 880 to 950-ish fps and will take down a target without exiting & causing collateral damage. And they can bust an engine block, an additional useful option. Being a semi-auto, you can't drop the pressure below that or it won't cycle & reload.

Back to .38 Special: a 140 or 165 grain hollow point at 1100 fps is a hard hit on a meat target. You really don't need anything else, and that can be packed into an "unfailable", 3" barrel, light weight wheelgun. A .357 or .41 mag. is nice insurance, but almost always big overkill and a lot of gun to carry & shoot. A .357 is nice to also fire .38s in it.
